22/11/2004
BANJA LUKA, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- Republika Srpska President Dragan Cavic visits Belgrade on Monday (22 November). He and Serbian counterpart Boris Tadic are expected to discuss issues related to co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal. Cavic says he intends to ask Serbia-Montenegro to hand over all RS indictees thought to be hiding on its territory, in the face of potential sanctions by the international community. 
In other news, Wilfred Martens, chairman of the BiH Police Restructuring Commission, visited Banja Luka on Friday to discuss police reform with members of the RS Parliament. Martens urged BiH politicians to reach consensus on the reform, especially the crucial issue of establishing a single police structure in the country. 
Also Friday, Iraqi Human Rights Minister Bakhtiar Amin arrived in BiH to discuss Sarajevo's experience with using DNA technology to identify war crimes victims. Iraq needs the technology to help identify victims of Saddam Hussein's regime. (Danas, Nezavisne novine - 22/11/04; Fena, Beta, PBS BiH, AFP - 21/11/04; Fena - 19/11/04) 
